00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:23.000
when we go out every single guy has a detailed battle map of the whole area of operations.

519
00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:28.000
To think that you have a section leader that doesn't even have a map,

520
00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
that's crazy.

521
00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
And then the number designations he talks about,

522
00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.000
when you know you hear about Hills 348 or whatever,

523
00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.000
he doesn't even know what those are.

524
00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:40.000
Back to the book, we only knew to move, attack,

525
00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:45.000
and defend unknown Hills that would stop the North Koreans from breaking through and capturing the city of Tegu.

526
00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:47.000
This was our world,

527
00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:51.000
following orders fighting for one another, being successful,

528
00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.000
and somehow surviving.

529
00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:02.000
Now they're sort of in a little low in the fighting,

530
00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:07.000
and one of his guys comes over, the guy's name is Gray.

531
00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:08.000
I'm not feeling very good.

532
00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.000
I need to sit down for a few minutes, Gray said,

533
00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
his head was pounding and he felt dizzy.

534
00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
Try to come over as soon as you can.

535
00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:16.000
Are you going to be alright?

536
00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:18.000
Yeah, just give me a few minutes.

537
00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
When we got to the other side of the ridge,

538
00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:23.000
I turned and looked back at Gray sitting on a tree stump.

539
00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.000
He had his head in his hands.

540
00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.000
Now we know what this is a symbol of, right?

541
00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.000
This is a symbol of like a little bit of combat stress happening,

542
00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:33.000
but he's just trying to get it together.

543
00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:36.000
Gray and Wall should have been great squad leaders,

544
00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
and I hope you is okay.

545
00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
I needed him to, I needed him and his leadership.

546
00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:45.000
I had taken off my helmet to wipe away some sweat,

547
00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:50.000
when Gray and the stump suddenly disappeared in a fireball,

548
00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:53.000
and artillery round landed right on him.

549
00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:58.000
I was stunned and just stood on the ridge looking at the smoking crater.

550
00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.000
Something happens to men who see combat.

551
00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:06.000
No matter how you try, you cannot make death invisible.

552
00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:09.000
It is there with you every moment.

553
00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:13.000
That split second would be seared into my mind for the rest of my life.

554
00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:17.000
But at that time, we didn't have time to mourn Gray.

555
00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
We had to get dug in, start digging.

556
00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
That round has us zeroed,

557
00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:26.000
and the barrage will be coming next, I said, grabbing Walls.

558
00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
Get all over and take charge of Gray's squad.

559
00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.000
Tell them I'll be over there to talk to him later.

560
00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:36.000
For the rest of the day, I kept the men busy.

561
00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:39.000
Anything to keep their minds off Gray.

562
00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:43.000
So let's think about that again.

563
00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:48.000
You can see that Richardson is legit.

564
00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:52.000
And this is your classic situation where this horrible thing,

565
00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.000
you witness this horrible thing, everyone sees it.

566
00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:59.000
And what does he say? Hey, look, and this is horrifying.

567
00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:02.000
You say, oh, they have us zeroed in.

568
00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:05.000
So where the rest of the next round is going to hit, they're going to hit all around us.

569
00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:08.000
So what we need to do is dig in and we need to do it now.

570
00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:11.000
And then he just immediately says, hall, go take over Gray's squad.

571
00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:14.000
Look, Gray's gone. We need to move on.

572
00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:17.000
Tell them I'll be over to talk to him later.

573
00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:23.000
Back to the book.

574
00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:26.000
What drove me more than anything was a positive outlook.

575
00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:30.000
And the fact that my men were watching everything I did.

576
00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:35.000
I often wondered when we were moving down the road went went through their minds.

577
00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.000
This is something that every leader should be thinking about all the time.

578
00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.000
Is that everyone's watching you?

579
00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
Your boys are watching you.

580
00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
And they're judging you.

581
00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.000
As harsh as that sound, that's what's happening.

582
00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:49.000
So you know what? Give them a good example.

583
00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:56.000
I'll tell you what. When I see leaders in the seal teams that didn't act that way,

584
00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:02.000
that didn't act as if they were being watched all the time, they usually slacked off.

585
00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:04.000
Like, what does that look like?

586
00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.000
Where? Oh, what it looks like.

587
00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:09.000
I mean, yeah, like, hey, oh, no, no, I can be a little bit late.

588
00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:11.000
No one's watching. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

589
00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
That's a big one. Oh, it's okay.

590
00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:17.000
I don't need this piece of gear. Oh, I'll cut the corner on this thing.

591
00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.000
Just all those little tiny things.

592
00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:22.000
And not to mention when you're in a situation like this,

593
00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.000
when you're watching you, when you say, hey, you know what?

594
00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.000
They got a style then we need to get dug in now.

595
00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:29.000
Hall, you got that gray squad now. Get to it.

596
00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:30.000
They're watching that too.

597
00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:31.000
Yeah.

598
00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
And they're seeing and going, okay, they're judging.

599
00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
And what are they judging? They're judging positive.

600
00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
They're judging that Richardson's got to shit together.

601
00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
And he's going to take care of them.

602
00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:44.000
Mm-hmm.

603
00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:47.000
Back to the book. It had to be a lot tougher on them than on me.

604
00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:52.000
While they had only death dwell on, I had dozens of other things

605
00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:55.000
that I must be thinking about and prepared for what was ahead.

606
00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:58.000
Where would I be if I were a North Korean?

607
00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.000
How would I react if we got hit from the right or left?

608
00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:05.000
How was our ammunition? Water was the bore sighting of the gun still all right.

609
00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
Where were the men taking care of their feet?

610
00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:12.000
So he's saying this correctly so, but this is kind of a different twist.

611
00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:16.000
Is, you know, a lot of times you hear the leader say, well, I was responsible for all these guys

612
00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:17.000
and that was a heavier weight.

613
00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:21.000
But for him, he's thinking, I was busy with all these other things.

614
00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:24.000
All these other guys had to do is think about the fact that they're about to die.

615
00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:25.000
Mm-hmm.

616
00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.000
And how that's actually hargur on them.

617
00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:28.000
Right.

618
00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:36.000
See, if you go into it with the perspective that everything's for you is hargur.

619
00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:39.000
And for everything, you know, for me it's hargur, because I'm a leader,

620
00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:45.000
whereas his attitude is fantastic, which is look, I'm the luxury of having other things to think about.

621
00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:49.000
These poor guys, they're just thinking about them being overrun.

622
00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:55.000
As opposed to if your attitude was flipped and you were thinking, I have it so hard,

623
00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
but these guys have it so easy.

624
00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
They will sense that.

625
00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:00.000
Yeah.

626
00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:05.000
And that's not going to end up net positive for you and your leadership.

627
00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:10.000
Back to book, the next North Korean assault started with screams and machine gun fire,

628
00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.000
but we beat it back with mortars in our own machine gun fire.

629
00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:18.000
Running between holes, I made sure everybody was ready for the next wave.

630
00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
Walsh had his section up and ready to fire.

631
00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:26.000
Hall was also ready, which was impressive, since he had just taken over from gray.

632
00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
The second attack was worse.

633
00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:32.000
The North Koreans were less than 50 yards from us.

634
00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:38.000
As I fired at the shadows moving toward us, I heard a frantic voice come over the radio.

635
00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:42.000
Roy Rogers III, the voice said in a deep southern draw,

636
00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
I need more firepower.

637
00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:45.000
I need more firepower.

638
00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:46.000
I'm about to get overrun.

639
00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:50.000
It was lieutenant Jim Brown from the bulltune that was on our left.

640
00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.000
I hope to hell he got more fire support.

641
00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:56.000
We were all hanging by a thread.

642
00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:01.000
Dead North Korean soldiers were stacking up in front of our foxholes,

643
00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:05.000
but they kept coming, wave after wave.

644
00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:09.000
I could hear walls screaming at the mend to stay in their holes.

645
00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:16.000
I was frantically changing the magazine in my car being as two of the North Koreans were within ten feet of me.

646
00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:21.000
Walsh and Hall saw them too, and opened fire, cutting the North Korean soldiers down.

647
00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:24.000
I saw another North Korean to my right and fired.

648
00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:27.000
He staggered back and dropped to the ground.

649
00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:31.000
I stayed low in my foxhole and kept firing straight ahead.

650
00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:38.000
Hall and Walsh kept firing to the rear, hitting the North Koreans attempting to move through our position.

651
00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:44.000
We had them in a crossfire, and in minutes our position was littered with North Korean bodies.

652
00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:49.000
Slighting a fresh magazine into my car being, I poked my head up,

653
00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:53.000
waiting for the next wave, but it never came.

654
00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:58.000
Stay alert. Some of them may still be alive.

655
00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:01.000
If you see any movement, shoot them.

656
00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:05.000
We waited a few minutes and finally climbed out.

657
00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:10.000
Check around your holes for live Koreans.

658
00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:19.000
And he goes on to say that we dragged the rest of the bodies away from our position and piled them to one side.

659
00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.000
I didn't even look at their faces.

660
00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:27.000
And he talks about the fact that his medics would try and take care of the North Korean wounded soldiers.

661
00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:30.000
That's pretty impressive.

662
00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:33.000
Back to the book, as daylight peaked over, it's head over the hills.

663
00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:38.000
A tall scrubby looking infantryman carrying a carbine approach me from out of the mist.

664
00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:43.000
As you got closer, I saw the small white cross painted on his helmet.

665
00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:46.000
He stuck out his hand as he approached.

666
00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:51.000
Chaplain Kapon, he said, giving me a firm handshake. Where are you from?

667
00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:58.000
Chaplain Amel Kapon from Pilsen, Kansas was a Catholic father who joined the army toward the end of World War II.

668
00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:06.000
He served in Burma and India until May 1946. He returned home and was assigned a parish in Kansas.

669
00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:09.000
But he felt his calling was with the troops.

670
00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:12.000
So he rejoined the army in 1948.

671
00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:18.000
He joined us in Korea after spending a few months in Japan. His uniform was dirty and he liked the rest of us.

672
00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:19.000
Needed his shave.

673
00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:24.000
It was clear he'd spent the night up close to the fighting and not safely in the rear.

674
00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:28.000
There was a peacefulness about him, though, that put me at ease.

675
00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:31.000
A quiet confidence he seemed to care where I was from.

676
00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:35.000
And I watched him as he spoke to the rest of the section.

677
00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:39.000
Each time he asked a soldier where he was from, gave him a firm handshake.

678
00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:42.000
It was not long before he had us all smiling.

679
00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:47.000
When Kapon finished making his rounds, he sat down near my fox hole and took out his pipe.

680
00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:50.000
It was missing most of its stem.

681
00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
What happened to your pipe?

682
00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:57.000
I asked as he filled it. A sniper he said, shot it out of my mouth a few days ago.

683
00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:00.000
We both had a laugh.

684
00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:03.000
I noticed that carbine laying across his lap.

685
00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:06.000
I thought Chaplain couldn't carry weapons.

686
00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:11.000
He smiled and nodded. If they're going to shoot at me, I'm going to be ready to shoot back.

687
00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:18.000
