There were dead and wounded all over everything was shot up it looked like an artillery barrage made a direct hit it was total chaos.

1594
01:37:41.000 --> 01:37:48.000
What are you two trying to do I asked they said they were trying to make contact with someone.

1595
01:37:48.000 --> 01:37:58.000
Sergeant on Taylor one of Walsers men the other guys from first battalion in the dark I didn't recognize him where's Walsh.

1596
01:37:58.000 --> 01:38:09.000
They're all dead serge Taylor said.

1597
01:38:09.000 --> 01:38:27.000
So they make movement towards that battalion headquarters area and there's still some friendlies there we stumbled into the battalion headquarters area and I introduced myself and asked Jones what the situation was it was not good.

1598
01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:40.000
There were thirty or forty wounded or dead doc Anderson in the chaplain and are in the command post trying to take care of the wounded.

1599
01:38:40.000 --> 01:38:48.000
Jones thought the battalion commander was dead they just walked in on them and shot up the whole damn place.

1600
01:38:48.000 --> 01:39:00.000
So at this point they kind of ziggy out of there into a tree line and we got into the wood line and threw ourselves to the ground completely exhausted.

1601
01:39:00.000 --> 01:39:10.000
And from there the chaplain moved onto another position but before he left he told me we were fighting the Chinese.

1602
01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:18.000
We heard rumors about the Chinese soldiers coming over the border that pretty much confirmed what I had fought for the last couple of hours.

1603
01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:25.000
Jones basically told me when he mentioned that their quilted uniform jackets looked much different than the North Koreans.

1604
01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:40.000
First Lieutenant Phil Peterson and Walt Mayo had also scrambled into our perimeter both officers were artillery forward observers but had lost their radios in the confusion.

1605
01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:56.000
The Chinese soldiers had crossed the Yalu to protect electrical generators along the river. That night Peterson had seen a Chinese prisoner in his quilted jacket but had no idea the danger we were in.

1606
01:39:56.000 --> 01:40:09.000
We had been ordered back to the battalion and then tried to escape when artillery unit tried to save their own hoursers. But the Chinese had already cut the road.

1607
01:40:09.000 --> 01:40:12.000
We were trapped.

1608
01:40:12.000 --> 01:40:25.000
We set up our defenses. We knew the Chinese would come for us that night. So that's it right now they're surrounded.

1609
01:40:25.000 --> 01:40:35.000
They set up a perimeter to the best of their ability and they got a bunch of wounded. They're low on ammunition. They're low on food. They're low on water.

1610
01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:43.000
So a perimeter is basically for those that don't know you set up 360 degree security perimeter. You dig some foxholes. You put machine guns pointing out.

1611
01:40:43.000 --> 01:40:53.000
It's your last stand situation now. It doesn't always last end because when you're on a normal patrol you set up perimeter. Any time you stop you set up 360 degree security.

1612
01:40:53.000 --> 01:41:09.000
And in this situation that's what they're doing. They're set up their perimeter to the best of their ability with what they've got left and then there's a little command post in the center of the perimeter. And here we go back to the book inside the command post. I knew what the officers were talking about.

1613
01:41:09.000 --> 01:41:12.000
It was a forbidden subject.

1614
01:41:12.000 --> 01:41:22.000
What were we going to do with the wounded in the terrible final moment that everyone knew is coming.

1615
01:41:22.000 --> 01:41:31.000
Italian surgeon, doc Anderson and the chaplain were doing what they could for about 40 wounded men. But we couldn't hold out for long without a relief column.

1616
01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:47.000
Meaning people coming to back them up. And if we had to run the wounded officers were going to have to decide whether or not to leave themselves and the other wounded men behind to the mercies of the enemy.

1617
01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:58.000
And once he kind of hears that inside the center of the perimeter during the at the command post there he goes back out to his edge of the perimeter.

1618
01:41:58.000 --> 01:42:04.000
And then here we go back to the book. I saw a group of 20 men running right at us.

1619
01:42:04.000 --> 01:42:11.000
They were Americans and we're hallowing and waving at us. I prayed they were the lead element of a relief column.

1620
01:42:11.000 --> 01:42:17.000
Because of course they're here in rumors that someone's going to come. There's there's friendly on the way. That's what they're getting. They're kind of.

1621
01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:27.000
And I wasn't clear where they were getting those rumors from or whether they were just assuming like hey we're here Americans are going to come to get us.

1622
01:42:27.000 --> 01:42:30.000
They've got to be sending a relief battalion. We just need to hang on.

1623
01:42:30.000 --> 01:42:35.000
So that's what he's saying. I prayed that they were the lead element of a relief column.

1624
01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:43.000
The other guys were cheering them on as they made the short dash to our trench. They slid inside their chest. Chess heaving.

1625
01:42:43.000 --> 01:42:47.000
What unit are you guys from I asked?

1626
01:42:47.000 --> 01:42:53.000
Second of the eighth an officer said between deep breaths.

1627
01:42:53.000 --> 01:43:01.000
The stragglers pushed by us and collapsed in the center of the perimeter. Everyone's morale sank lower than whale shit.

1628
01:43:01.000 --> 01:43:09.000
The energy and excitement seemed to deflate from the men in the trench and all at once their heads hung and shoulders dipped.

1629
01:43:09.000 --> 01:43:17.000
These guys weren't a relief column. They were just more stragglers from the second battalion.

1630
01:43:17.000 --> 01:43:33.000
I couldn't shake the thought that no one was coming for us.

1631
01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:41.000
There's a soldier that he talks about a Polish guy. I mean American guy but of Polish descent last name's a wallock.

1632
01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:49.000
Later that day, well, I saw another in their perimeter. Later that day wallock sent for me. I walked across the west side of the perimeter and saw him standing near a machine gun position.

1633
01:43:49.000 --> 01:43:55.000
He looked concerned and started pointing out towards what looked like an open field.

1634
01:43:55.000 --> 01:44:01.000
Look over there, he said. I watched where he was pointing. I didn't see anything.

1635
01:44:01.000 --> 01:44:07.000
I looked at him and shrug my soldiers. No, keep looking. He said this time staring intently.

1636
01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:13.000
Then I saw it. A faint shovelful of dirt flying right into the air.

1637
01:44:13.000 --> 01:44:21.000
The little bastards were digging a trench. They were about a half dozen or so digging a path right for us.

1638
01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:29.000
Our machine guns had been keeping them at a distance but when their trench was done, they could move under cover right up to the edge of our trenches.

1639
01:44:29.000 --> 01:44:37.000
So that's a determined enemy. They're just going to spend all day digging toward you.

1640
01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:45.000
As clandestine as they can but they can only keep it so clandestine and no one will only only one soldier noticed.

1641
01:44:45.000 --> 01:44:53.000
Back to the book, sunset was a bad time. Night always meant another attack.

1642
01:44:53.000 --> 01:44:57.000
It started with a probe. A few Chinese soldiers would move up to the perimeter followed by a short violent firefight.

1643
01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:11.000
Shortly after the probe, the artillery and mortar fire would start followed by the demonic ball of brass bugles and whistles as the Chinese infantry attacked.

1644
01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:15.000
The now he's talking about his guys. The men looked at me with weary, entire dyes.

1645
01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:23.000
All of us had scruffy beards and our skin was caked with mud and blood. None of the soldiers could look at me.

1646
01:45:23.000 --> 01:45:29.000
They knew that they wouldn't survive unless they got up and fought but they just sat there.

1647
01:45:29.000 --> 01:45:35.000
They were not cowards just frozen by fear. For some, this was their first taste of combat.

1648
01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:41.000
Boys who overnight were forced to become men. I could only imagine the terror they must have been through.

1649
01:45:41.000 --> 01:45:43.000
Must have been going through.

1650
01:45:43.000 --> 01:45:46.000
You've got two choices. I yelled.

1651
01:45:46.000 --> 01:45:51.000
Get up and get to the line or I'll shoot you.

1652
01:45:51.000 --> 01:45:55.000
That shocked them into action. I don't think they thought I would shoot them.

1653
01:45:55.000 --> 01:46:03.000
I had no sooner finish prodding the men out of their interior holes than one hell of a fight took place at the Batayan command post.

1654
01:46:03.000 --> 01:46:09.000
I knew there were mostly wounded soldiers there and I feared for Jones the lone man on the machine gun.

1655
01:46:09.000 --> 01:46:15.000
But I had my own problems. The bugles and whistles broke the silence and the Chinese rushed the east side of our perimeter.

1656
01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:19.000
They came in waves straight into our fire.

1657
01:46:19.000 --> 01:46:23.000
As quickly as they fell more appeared.

1658
01:46:23.000 --> 01:46:25.000
They moved into our fire like they were possessed.

1659
01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:29.000
I raced from trench to trench moving men where the Chinese concentrated their attack.

1660
01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:35.000
When they were attacked on the east side slowed, they launched an attack on the west side.

1661
01:46:35.000 --> 01:46:37.000
Although we were dug in our casualties, we're mounting.

1662
01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:45.000
I kept moving men to where the most Chinese were concentrated. The attack slowed down but it was not long before they began an assault on the west side of the perimeter.

1663
01:46:45.000 --> 01:46:49.000
Now they get this idea as these attack were taken place.

1664
01:46:49.000 --> 01:46:51.000
There's these trucks that were there.

1665
01:46:51.000 --> 01:46:57.000
Kind of abandoned trucks and they figure it's night time if they can set these trucks on fire.

1666
01:46:57.000 --> 01:47:01.000
They'll allow them to see the enemy.

1667
01:47:01.000 --> 01:47:05.000
And so that's what they do. They want one of these attack starts.

1668
01:47:05.000 --> 01:47:13.000
They shot the gas tanks and then shot tracers until all the vehicles were on fire.

1669
01:47:13.000 --> 01:47:17.000
When the Chinese infantry men ran past, we could see them silhouetted against the light.

1670
01:47:17.000 --> 01:47:25.000
It was a shooting gallery. We cut down the first wave only to watch the next one's climb over their comrades and keep coming.

1671
01:47:25.000 --> 01:47:29.000
We mowed down the next wave, but they still kept coming.

1672
01:47:29.000 --> 01:47:33.000
For the rest of the night, the Chinese came at us like waves to the shore.

1673
01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:37.000
But each time we stopped them, they never reached the perimeter.

1674
01:47:37.000 --> 01:47:40.000
The next morning we took stock of our situation.

1675
01:47:40.000 --> 01:47:46.000
Water and food were a problem, but ammunition and the wounded were our biggest concern.

1676
01:47:46.000 --> 01:47:52.000
We had 85 able-bodied men left out of about 200.

1677
01:47:52.000 --> 01:47:56.000
The rest were dead or wounded.

1678
01:47:56.000 --> 01:48:04.000
We were also out of morphine and the screams of the wounded were starting to have an impact on the rest of the men.

1679
01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:08.000
I could see in their eyes a tired, haggard look.

1680
01:48:08.000 --> 01:48:12.000
A relief column is coming for us. They'll get through today.

1681
01:48:12.000 --> 01:48:14.000
I told the men as I walked the line.

1682
01:48:14.000 --> 01:48:18.000
I said it over and over again, hoping to climb them.

1683
01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:22.000
And as I realized in hindsight, probably hoping to convince myself.

1684
01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:26.000
I hope to hell I was right.

1685
01:48:26.000 --> 01:48:36.000
Now, this is just a little report again about Chaplain Coplan.

1686
01:48:36.000 --> 01:48:40.000
He gets a report.

1687
01:48:40.000 --> 01:48:42.000
Richardson gets a report.

1688
01:48:42.000 --> 01:48:46.000
And it says this, the doc said that when the Chinese got into the dugout,

1689
01:48:46.000 --> 01:48:50.000
Chaplain Coplan stopped them from killing all the wounded by surrendering himself.

1690
01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:54.000
The Chinese took him and 15 of the walking wounded,

1691
01:48:54.000 --> 01:48:58.000
including my old company commander Captain McAbee.

1692
01:48:58.000 --> 01:49:02.000
What Coplan did was heroic stopping the Chinese.

1693
01:49:02.000 --> 01:49:06.000
When he left, he was carrying Sergeant Miller.

1694
01:49:06.000 --> 01:49:12.000
So Chaplain Coplan just once again, heroic actions,

1695
01:49:12.000 --> 01:49:16.000
saving the lives of these guys before they were slaughtered by the Chinese,

1696
01:49:16.000 --> 01:49:20.000
by surrendering himself.

1697
01:49:20.000 --> 01:49:28.000
When I got back, I organized about a dozen guys to follow me out of the perimeter and gather up some of the Chinese weapons and ammunition.

1698
01:49:28.000 --> 01:49:34.000
We were out of almost everything, but lying in front of us were weapons and ammunition, including much needed grenades.

1699
01:49:34.000 --> 01:49:38.000
Before we left, I told the men to be careful because some of the Chinese might still be alive.

1700
01:49:38.000 --> 01:49:44.000
It was gruesome business, but the only solution to our most pressing problem.

1701
01:49:44.000 --> 01:49:48.000
Crawling over piles of dead Chinese, the smell was overpowering.

1702
01:49:48.000 --> 01:49:54.000
At time, I could hear gas, seep out of the decaying corpses.

1703
01:49:54.000 --> 01:50:00.000
I could hear men behind me gag and throw up.

1704
01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:12.000
Yeah, so this is like, you got to sit around, you got to imagine what this is like, that they are the Chinese attackers are literally stacked and piled on top of one another.

1705
01:50:12.000 --> 01:50:18.000
And you're so low that you have to go out and gather weapons and ammunition from them.

1706
01:50:18.000 --> 01:50:34.000
And as you're doing that, their bloated bodies are giving off gases, and it's smell so horrible, and the whole scene is so horrific, that your men are dry-heaving and throwing up as you're trying to do this.

1707
01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:46.000
Back to the book. For the rest of the morning, we passed out our new trove of ammunition and dug in deeper.

1708
01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:49.000
As we worked, I heard the faint buzz of an airplane overhead.

1709
01:50:49.000 --> 01:50:57.000
The spotter plane that had dropped a bag of medical supplies was back, so I skipped over this part, but they got some medical supplies from a little plane.

1710
01:50:57.000 --> 01:51:05.000
And this time, instead of dropping supplies, it dropped the message. And this time, the pilot dropped it on target.

1711
01:51:05.000 --> 01:51:11.000
Guru, Guru, open the message. That's one of the one of the other guys, Guru.

1712
01:51:11.000 --> 01:51:17.000
I hope I'm pronouncing that right. G-I-R-O-U-X-G-R-O, open the message.

1713
01:51:17.000 --> 01:51:21.000
I saw the color leave as face.

1714
01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:32.000
I knew what the message said before he told me. We were on our own. No relief column was on its way. Our new order was simple.

1715
01:51:32.000 --> 01:51:37.000
We needed to get back to friendly lines the best way we could.

1716
01:51:37.000 --> 01:51:43.000
While Guru got the officers together, I gathered up a few of the sergeants and we had a meeting.

1717
01:51:43.000 --> 01:51:53.000
Well, we are on our own. That message told us to get back the best way we can. I told the sergeants.

1718
01:51:53.000 --> 01:51:57.000
While I was the first one to speak up, we can't just leave the wounded. What the hell else were we going to do with sergeant I didn't recognize said.

1719
01:51:57.000 --> 01:52:07.000
The meeting was tense. I realized that what I had been telling them was going to happen wasn't going to. No relief. No rescue.

1720
01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:17.000
And if we stayed in this hellhole, we would all die. I don't think we can keep the Chinese out of the perimeter for one more than one more night.

1721
01:52:17.000 --> 01:52:27.000
If we can even do that, I said. There was silence. We were facing death, but bravery is a funny thing.

1722
01:52:27.000 --> 01:52:33.000
It comes in all shapes and sizes and appears in men you would at least expect it from.

1723
01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:41.000
Most of us didn't know one another, but we fought hard together like we would blood brothers.

1724
01:52:41.000 --> 01:52:47.000
What do you say about staying one more night? Maybe somehow they will break through to us tomorrow.

1725
01:52:47.000 --> 01:52:59.000
I said tomorrow. We talk about the wounded. Wallach nodded his head and looked at the others. I'm for staying one more night.

1726
01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:07.000
Everyone quickly agreed. No one wanted to leave the wounded. I told Grow the way the men felt.

1727
01:53:07.000 --> 01:53:17.000
And after he met with bronzer male and Peterson they all agreed. No one was comfortable leaving our wounded or the wounded nearby in the battalion headquarters.

1728
01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:27.000
The Chinese, that night the Chinese attacked three times and three times we held, but not without suffering more casualties.

1729
01:53:27.000 --> 01:53:35.000
After the last attack I literally fell into a hole near the center of the perimeter. I was fighting a losing battle against sleep.

1730
01:53:35.000 --> 01:53:43.000
I could feel myself slipping away. My body felt numb, damp and heavy.

1731
01:53:43.000 --> 01:53:53.000
There was no noise, no sound. I was paralyzed in the hard drive tried to move. The more I felt, the more my body felt like stone.

1732
01:53:53.000 --> 01:53:59.000
I tried to scream. Nothing. I tried harder. I couldn't make a sound.

1733
01:53:59.000 --> 01:54:11.000
Bugles in the distance cleared my hazy mind. I could hear the burp burp of Chinese submachine guns, but the cop, but not the constant rattle of our own machine gun closest to me.

1734
01:54:11.000 --> 01:54:17.000
I instantly got a sick feeling. I bolted out of the trench and crawled toward the machine gun position and fell into the hole head first.

1735
01:54:17.000 --> 01:54:25.000
The gunner was wounded and the assistant gunner was trying to put the gun back in action. There was ammo, but the gun was jammed.

1736
01:54:25.000 --> 01:54:35.000
I racked it back, nothing. The head space was screwed up. The Chinese were within 20 yards of us, and I was screaming for the men to keep firing.

1737
01:54:35.000 --> 01:54:43.000
I pulled the gun into the hole and started to take it apart. I adjusted the head space, put the barrel in chamber and alignment, and reassembled it.

1738
01:54:43.000 --> 01:54:49.000
The A gunner, the assistant gunner, laid the ammo belt in and slapped the cover down.

1739
01:54:49.000 --> 01:54:57.000
I racked the bolt back and pulled the trigger. The gun jumped back to life. The fire immediately had an impact and drove a wedge into the advancing soldiers.

1740
01:54:57.000 --> 01:55:05.000
The first burst took out half a dozen. Some of the wounded and dead Chinese fell into our trenches.

1741
01:55:05.000 --> 01:55:11.000
Others crumbled in a heap near the edge, close enough that we could reach out and touch them.

1742
01:55:11.000 --> 01:55:19.000
I looked down and saw that the gunner was dead. The A gunner was hitting the arms, and I could see blood staining his fatigue jacket,

1743
01:55:19.000 --> 01:55:25.000
but he kept firing his rifle and replacing ammo belts when the machine gun went dry.

1744
01:55:25.000 --> 01:55:29.000
Just as fast as it started, the attack ended.

1745
01:55:29.000 --> 01:55:39.000
There was some sporadic firing from the other side of the perimeter. A couple of guys close to the gun position came over to me and took over.

1746
01:55:39.000 --> 01:55:45.000
As I headed back to my hole, I crawled over several dead American and Chinese.

1747
01:55:45.000 --> 01:55:55.000
Every trench and hole seemed to be filled with wounded men screaming and crying for their mothers.

1748
01:55:55.000 --> 01:55:59.000
Always their mothers.

1749
01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:05.000
We had an added problem now since some of the wounded were Chinese soldiers.

1750
01:56:05.000 --> 01:56:09.000
The dead were not a problem. We just pushed them out in front of the trench,

1751
01:56:09.000 --> 01:56:13.000
but the wounded we had to help if we could.

1752
01:56:13.000 --> 01:56:19.000
The medics did their best, but we barely had enough for our own men.

1753
01:56:19.000 --> 01:56:25.000
The Chinese were all scared to death, crying, and moaning.

1754
01:56:25.000 --> 01:56:31.000
They were the enemy, but they were also soldiers just like us.

1755
01:56:31.000 --> 01:56:37.000
It was difficult to see them that way.

1756
01:56:37.000 --> 01:56:45.000
The next morning, bronzer and grower called me over to them.

1757
01:56:45.000 --> 01:56:49.000
The two artillery lieutenant's male and putters and were also there, grower said,

1758
01:56:49.000 --> 01:56:53.000
what we all knew. We can't stay here any longer.

1759
01:56:53.000 --> 01:56:57.000
There is no doubt my mind that the Chinese will overrun us tonight.

1760
01:56:57.000 --> 01:57:01.000
We need to find a way out. We'll lead a patrol.

1761
01:57:01.000 --> 01:57:07.000
Lieutenant's male and peaters have already volunteered to go.

1762
01:57:07.000 --> 01:57:13.000
I looked at the lieutenant's and nodded my head, yes.

1763
01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:19.000
They're going to find a way out of this perimeter,

1764
01:57:19.000 --> 01:57:23.000
and they're going to do a little reconnaissance tonight,

1765
01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:31.000
or now to try and figure out their route. So that then later they can get out of there and come up with a plan to get out of there.

1766
01:57:31.000 --> 01:57:35.000
Back to the book, because we, and so they're crawling down a trench to try and look for the way out.

1767
01:57:35.000 --> 01:57:39.000
As we crawled down the trench toward the east side,

1768
01:57:39.000 --> 01:57:41.000
word got out that we were going on patrol.

1769
01:57:41.000 --> 01:57:47.000
Peters and crawled by a badly wounded radio operator, lieutenant Petersen, where are you going?

1770
01:57:47.000 --> 01:57:51.000
Looking for a way out, he said.

1771
01:57:51.000 --> 01:57:55.000
Lieutenant Peterson, the radio operator pleaded, please don't leave me here.

1772
01:57:55.000 --> 01:57:59.000
Please don't leave me. You can't leave me here for them to get me.

1773
01:58:01.000 --> 01:58:07.000
Petersen looked shaken, and I urged us forward. I heard him say he was sorry as we crawled off.

1774
01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:15.000
Others reached out to us, patded us on the back, and wished us good luck.

1775
01:58:15.000 --> 01:58:19.000
As we moved down the riverbed, the Chinese soldiers,

1776
01:58:19.000 --> 01:58:25.000
grabbed at us, and held out cops begging for water.

1777
01:58:25.000 --> 01:58:29.000
I took my canteen and turned it upside down to show them that we had no water.

1778
01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:33.000
So there's the enemy. They're also wounded laying in these trenches.

1779
01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:39.000
It's just a total bloodbath, and the Chinese soldiers are asking these Americans.

