they come back and put out the word.

1788
01:59:22.000 --> 01:59:26.000
Like, okay, this is what we're going to try and do.

1789
01:59:26.000 --> 01:59:32.000
And it's a grote talking. He says, we moved it 1700 before the Chinese move in.

1790
01:59:32.000 --> 01:59:37.000
Grote said, word was passed to all able bodied men.

1791
01:59:37.000 --> 01:59:42.000
They were told to make sure that they took what ammunition they had left.

1792
01:59:42.000 --> 01:59:47.000
I got a burp gun and some ammo.

1793
01:59:47.000 --> 01:59:51.000
The wounded men knew what was happening.

1794
01:59:51.000 --> 01:59:56.000
Some broke down, cried, and begged us not to leave.

1795
01:59:56.000 --> 02:00:02.000
Please, dear God, take us. One soldier begged me, grabbing at my shirt.

1796
02:00:02.000 --> 02:00:05.000
Don't leave us to the Chinese.

1797
02:00:05.000 --> 02:00:10.000
Others just watched in silence.

1798
02:00:10.000 --> 02:00:14.000
They knew they'd slow us down.

1799
02:00:14.000 --> 02:00:18.000
They also knew that they'd be dead soon.

1800
02:00:18.000 --> 02:00:23.000
They simply asked that we come back for them.

1801
02:00:23.000 --> 02:00:28.000
But I knew we were leaving them to die or worse, get captured.

1802
02:00:28.000 --> 02:00:33.000
I knew my orders and agreed with them.

1803
02:00:33.000 --> 02:00:38.000
But I couldn't shake the feeling that I was leaving so many good men.

1804
02:00:38.000 --> 02:00:43.000
Men who'd fought well only to be left behind to die.

1805
02:00:43.000 --> 02:00:49.000
I wasn't sure I could ever forget this.

1806
02:00:49.000 --> 02:00:58.000
This was the hardest thing I had done in my short lifetime.

1807
02:00:58.000 --> 02:01:03.000
This is your classic scenario of, hey, what do we do?

1808
02:01:03.000 --> 02:01:06.000
We leave no man behind.

1809
02:01:06.000 --> 02:01:12.000
So then what's going to happen if they do that is everyone is going to die.

1810
02:01:12.000 --> 02:01:14.000
And they make the decision.

1811
02:01:14.000 --> 02:01:18.000
Now we could have a theoretical debate on well,

1812
02:01:18.000 --> 02:01:21.000
maybe if they fought it out, maybe if they stuck together,

1813
02:01:21.000 --> 02:01:26.000
maybe they could defeat the Chinese that are surrounding them.

1814
02:01:26.000 --> 02:01:31.000
In my estimation, this is wrong.

1815
02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:33.000
And you can see these guys already stayed longer.

1816
02:01:33.000 --> 02:01:35.000
They've already done everything that they can.

1817
02:01:35.000 --> 02:01:36.000
They're out of ammunition.

1818
02:01:36.000 --> 02:01:42.000
They're surrounded by Chinese that Chinese have unlimited number of men that are literally in piles around them.

1819
02:01:42.000 --> 02:01:48.000
And they know that if they are going to, if anyone is going to survive,

1820
02:01:48.000 --> 02:01:50.000
then they need to make a break for it.

1821
02:01:50.000 --> 02:01:53.000
And again, it's theoretical for us that it's sitting here.

1822
02:01:53.000 --> 02:01:54.000
It's hypothetical.

1823
02:01:54.000 --> 02:01:57.000
We could say, oh, we'd stay in fight. We could say whatever you want to say right now.

1824
02:01:57.000 --> 02:02:00.000
You're not in that position.

1825
02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:04.000
So now they leave it around five o'clock.

1826
02:02:04.000 --> 02:02:09.000
They start making a move a few hours into the march that rain turned into a downpour in minutes.

1827
02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:13.000
We were soaked to the skin. The temperature was dropping and started to shiver.

1828
02:02:13.000 --> 02:02:15.000
Moving was the only way to stay warm.

1829
02:02:15.000 --> 02:02:23.000
I pushed on trying to get as many miles as possible between us and the old perimeter.

1830
02:02:23.000 --> 02:02:26.000
We were well behind Chinese lines.

1831
02:02:26.000 --> 02:02:29.000
And because of the size of our group, it was likely that we'd be spotted soon.

1832
02:02:29.000 --> 02:02:31.000
Now this is interesting.

1833
02:02:31.000 --> 02:02:35.000
Trying to move with, I think they said they had 80 able bodied men.

1834
02:02:35.000 --> 02:02:38.000
Maybe at 60, that's a massive number of people.

1835
02:02:38.000 --> 02:02:40.000
You can't hide 60 people.

1836
02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:42.000
It doesn't work.

1837
02:02:42.000 --> 02:02:44.000
You can, oh well, I shouldn't say you can't.

1838
02:02:44.000 --> 02:02:47.000
It's very, very difficult to hide 60 people.

1839
02:02:47.000 --> 02:02:49.000
Like a platoon of 40 guys.

1840
02:02:49.000 --> 02:02:54.000
It's hard, you know, in the sealed teams, we have little tiny elements,

1841
02:02:54.000 --> 02:02:56.000
little tiny platoon of 16 guys.

1842
02:02:56.000 --> 02:03:00.000
You can find some terrain that will hide you.

1843
02:03:00.000 --> 02:03:03.000
We've worked in squads with eight guys.

1844
02:03:03.000 --> 02:03:05.000
Like, okay, we can find a place to hide.

1845
02:03:05.000 --> 02:03:10.000
When you have 60 or 80 guys behind enemy lines, that's going to be a challenge.

1846
02:03:10.000 --> 02:03:13.000
I mean, just think about where can you hide that many people.

1847
02:03:13.000 --> 02:03:16.000
Like a perfect terrain feature.

1848
02:03:16.000 --> 02:03:18.000
A ravine, you know, something like that.

1849
02:03:18.000 --> 02:03:22.000
That's a lot of people to put in the ravine and just the noise discipline of people.

1850
02:03:22.000 --> 02:03:23.000
You know, who's going to cough?

1851
02:03:23.000 --> 02:03:25.000
You get 60 people.

1852
02:03:25.000 --> 02:03:26.000
Someone's going to cough.

1853
02:03:26.000 --> 02:03:29.000
I mean, just you and me sitting in this room and we notice one of us

1854
02:03:29.000 --> 02:03:34.000
costs because we're one of us grunts or whatever, because we're recording it.

1855
02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:38.000
But you think about, you know, you nice sitting here for two hours for three hours.

1856
02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:43.000
I would say five times during that one of us will cough.

1857
02:03:43.000 --> 02:03:44.000
Right?

1858
02:03:44.000 --> 02:03:46.000
And you got to go edit it out.

1859
02:03:46.000 --> 02:03:48.000
Sure.

1860
02:03:48.000 --> 02:03:55.000
So if that's happening with two of us, you put 80 people into ravine where they're trying to hide from the enemy.

1861
02:03:55.000 --> 02:03:57.000
And there's how many people are coughing.

1862
02:03:57.000 --> 02:04:01.000
You know, how many people are sneezing?

1863
02:04:01.000 --> 02:04:02.000
Right?

1864
02:04:02.000 --> 02:04:04.000
And it's not, it's not good odds.

1865
02:04:04.000 --> 02:04:06.000
And that's where these guys are saying.

1866
02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:08.000
He is Richardson saying, look, we have a massive group.

1867
02:04:08.000 --> 02:04:12.000
It's not going to be easy to hide.

1868
02:04:12.000 --> 02:04:13.000
Back to the book.

1869
02:04:13.000 --> 02:04:17.000
Get moving to take advantage of the dark.

1870
02:04:17.000 --> 02:04:18.000
I left the house.

1871
02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:20.000
They had been in a little house speaking of hiding.

1872
02:04:20.000 --> 02:04:22.000
I left the house frustrated.

1873
02:04:22.000 --> 02:04:25.000
Sergeant Mayor from the Batyans intelligence section called me over.

1874
02:04:25.000 --> 02:04:26.000
Let's get out of here.

1875
02:04:26.000 --> 02:04:29.000
He said, you and I have a better chance to get back to this group as two large.

1876
02:04:29.000 --> 02:04:33.000
We don't have the fire power to fight and they're slowing us down.

1877
02:04:33.000 --> 02:04:35.000
So here's a guy saying, let Barrow.

1878
02:04:35.000 --> 02:04:36.000
Losers make a run for it.

1879
02:04:36.000 --> 02:04:38.000
He was right.

1880
02:04:38.000 --> 02:04:42.000
I knew that we'd probably make it back to friendly lines together.

1881
02:04:42.000 --> 02:04:46.000
Breaking down in a smaller group would be better.

1882
02:04:46.000 --> 02:04:51.000
But I'd help the Shepherd these men too far to turn my back on them,

1883
02:04:51.000 --> 02:04:53.000
even if it cost me my life.

1884
02:04:53.000 --> 02:04:55.000
Sorry.

1885
02:04:55.000 --> 02:04:56.000
Can't do it.

1886
02:04:56.000 --> 02:05:00.000
Mayor shrugged and disappeared into the darkness.

1887
02:05:00.000 --> 02:05:03.000
So exactly what I just said, this guy made the decision.

1888
02:05:03.000 --> 02:05:04.000
You know what?

1889
02:05:04.000 --> 02:05:06.000
Now, going alone, that's not a good idea either.

1890
02:05:06.000 --> 02:05:09.000
You know, because now you got no one to support you.

1891
02:05:09.000 --> 02:05:10.000
You got no one to watch your sex.

1892
02:05:10.000 --> 02:05:12.000
I mean, that's just a bad idea.

1893
02:05:12.000 --> 02:05:15.000
You can't, you can need to sleep at some point in your by yourself.

1894
02:05:15.000 --> 02:05:17.000
What happens when you start snoring?

1895
02:05:17.000 --> 02:05:18.000
Right?

1896
02:05:18.000 --> 02:05:19.000
Yeah.

1897
02:05:19.000 --> 02:05:21.000
But this guy figured I got a better chance to do it in the spine myself.

1898
02:05:21.000 --> 02:05:22.000
So I'm going to break out.

1899
02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:24.000
Now, you could have given a order like, hey,

1900
02:05:24.000 --> 02:05:27.000
everyone, there's something called a scape and invasion.

1901
02:05:27.000 --> 02:05:30.000
When you're just, everyone's basically every man from self.

1902
02:05:30.000 --> 02:05:32.000
You could do that.

1903
02:05:32.000 --> 02:05:37.000
But at this point, Richardson is like, hey, we made it this far.

1904
02:05:37.000 --> 02:05:39.000
We're going to stick together.

1905
02:05:39.000 --> 02:05:41.000
Back to the book.

1906
02:05:41.000 --> 02:05:43.000
My group climbed to the top of a null.

1907
02:05:43.000 --> 02:05:47.000
I could see the rounds hitting a mountain no more than five miles away.

1908
02:05:47.000 --> 02:05:50.000
We were close for the first time I felt hope.

1909
02:05:50.000 --> 02:05:54.000
Then the hail erupted with machine gun and mortar fire.

1910
02:05:54.000 --> 02:05:56.000
I was knocked flat on my face.

1911
02:05:56.000 --> 02:06:00.000
I quickly got up and just as quickly got back down in the prone position.

1912
02:06:00.000 --> 02:06:02.000
The Chinese were shelling the hail.

1913
02:06:02.000 --> 02:06:04.000
My lower back felt wet.

1914
02:06:04.000 --> 02:06:08.000
And I could feel what I thought was sweat running down the crack of my ass.

1915
02:06:08.000 --> 02:06:09.000
It wasn't sweat.

1916
02:06:09.000 --> 02:06:10.000
It was blood.

1917
02:06:10.000 --> 02:06:13.000
I was hit, but I didn't feel anything.

1918
02:06:13.000 --> 02:06:16.000
There was so much smoke, dirt and dust that I could barely see.

1919
02:06:16.000 --> 02:06:19.000
I stumbled off the hail followed by three others.

1920
02:06:19.000 --> 02:06:22.000
There were about a dozen Chinese soldiers chasing us.

1921
02:06:22.000 --> 02:06:24.000
I prodded myself to think and move.

1922
02:06:24.000 --> 02:06:27.000
We started to head for a village on the other side of the road.

1923
02:06:27.000 --> 02:06:31.000
Behind the village, I could see a massive rice patty that ran up to a hill.

1924
02:06:31.000 --> 02:06:34.000
I figured we could escape it if we got over the hill first.

1925
02:06:34.000 --> 02:06:38.000
The patty had about three or four inches of water in it.

1926
02:06:38.000 --> 02:06:42.000
We stayed on the tops of the dikes and got halfway across the patty before I turned

1927
02:06:42.000 --> 02:06:44.000
to fire back.

1928
02:06:44.000 --> 02:06:49.000
The Chinese soldiers dove for cover when they did we started running again.

1929
02:06:49.000 --> 02:06:53.000
As I was running, I saw rounds hitting the water in front of me.

1930
02:06:53.000 --> 02:06:57.000
It's not good.

1931
02:06:57.000 --> 02:07:03.000
When we got to the other side, we got down.

1932
02:07:03.000 --> 02:07:07.000
We got down behind the dike and started firing at the Chinese again.

1933
02:07:07.000 --> 02:07:09.000
I didn't see anyone behind them.

1934
02:07:09.000 --> 02:07:12.000
If we could take them out, we had a chance.

1935
02:07:12.000 --> 02:07:16.000
But the others didn't have any ammunition left.

1936
02:07:16.000 --> 02:07:19.000
And I was down to a few rounds myself.

1937
02:07:19.000 --> 02:07:22.000
Get going, I said.

1938
02:07:22.000 --> 02:07:24.000
I'll hold them off.

1939
02:07:24.000 --> 02:07:26.000
They looked at me for a second.

1940
02:07:26.000 --> 02:07:32.000
Go, I screamed and turned toward the Chinese soldiers crossing the patty.

1941
02:07:32.000 --> 02:07:35.000
I fired a few shots and then dove behind a dike.

1942
02:07:35.000 --> 02:07:41.000
A few seconds later, I fired two more bursts before I was out of ammunition.

1943
02:07:41.000 --> 02:07:44.000
Between bursts, my mind was searching for an escape route.

1944
02:07:44.000 --> 02:07:48.000
I knew that if I ran straight up the hill, I didn't stand a chance.

1945
02:07:48.000 --> 02:07:51.000
About 30 yards to my right, there was a house.

1946
02:07:51.000 --> 02:07:55.000
A woman in a baby were crying and wailing and a dugout near the hill.

1947
02:07:55.000 --> 02:07:56.000
I went into the house.

1948
02:07:56.000 --> 02:07:59.000
If I went into the house, I was sure the woman would tell them.

1949
02:07:59.000 --> 02:08:02.000
But I couldn't stay behind the dike with no ammunition.

1950
02:08:02.000 --> 02:08:05.000
Jumping up, I ran behind the house and started up the hill.

1951
02:08:05.000 --> 02:08:09.000
I tried to keep the house at my back hoping to mask my movement.

1952
02:08:09.000 --> 02:08:15.000
I went as far as I could go without the Chinese seeing me and then dove into a large bush.

1953
02:08:15.000 --> 02:08:20.000
Rolling onto my stomach with my Chinese burp gun underneath me, I waited.

1954
02:08:20.000 --> 02:08:24.000
I had no ammo, but I had a death grip on the weapon.

1955
02:08:24.000 --> 02:08:27.000
It was like my security blanket.

1956
02:08:27.000 --> 02:08:31.000
I could hear the Chinese soldiers climbing up the hill.

1957
02:08:31.000 --> 02:08:33.000
They were yelling at one another.

1958
02:08:33.000 --> 02:08:37.000
I was trying not to move, not even breathe.

1959
02:08:37.000 --> 02:08:42.000
A fly hovered around my face landing on my nose and mouth.

1960
02:08:42.000 --> 02:08:46.000
I tried to keep my mind closed to everything.

1961
02:08:46.000 --> 02:08:53.000
I closed my eyes as they passed and took my first breath as I heard their yelling behind me.

1962
02:08:53.000 --> 02:08:56.000
In a few minutes, I was sure they were gone.

1963
02:08:56.000 --> 02:08:59.000
But every unit has one.

1964
02:08:59.000 --> 02:09:02.000
A straggler that can't keep up.

1965
02:09:02.000 --> 02:09:09.000
The Chinese straggler was so slow that when he got close to the bush, he saw me.

1966
02:09:09.000 --> 02:09:12.000
I never moved and just shut my eyes.

1967
02:09:12.000 --> 02:09:15.000
He started to holler and drove his bayonet into my butt.

1968
02:09:15.000 --> 02:09:18.000
I felt the tip hit the bone.

1969
02:09:18.000 --> 02:09:21.000
When I opened my eyes, I saw boots all around me.

1970
02:09:21.000 --> 02:09:26.000
My mind went to the burp gun.

1971
02:09:26.000 --> 02:09:31.000
If I rolled over, holding it, they'd shoot me for sure.

1972
02:09:31.000 --> 02:09:38.000
I shot my arms out along the ground and rolled over, leaving the burp gun in the mud.

1973
02:09:38.000 --> 02:09:42.000
They reached down and jerked me up.

1974
02:09:42.000 --> 02:09:45.000
The barrel of the pistol looked like a gun.

1975
02:09:45.000 --> 02:09:53.000
The barrel of the pistol looked like the business end of 105 millimeter hawitzer.

1976
02:09:53.000 --> 02:09:59.000
A Chinese officer with red piping down the side of his pants had the pistol pressed between my eyes.

1977
02:09:59.000 --> 02:10:02.000
He was screaming at me and Chinese, pointing up the hill.

1978
02:10:02.000 --> 02:10:04.000
I was numb and couldn't speak.

1979
02:10:04.000 --> 02:10:06.000
I lifted my shoulders and left them drop.

1980
02:10:06.000 --> 02:10:10.000
I thought of this moment many times.

1981
02:10:10.000 --> 02:10:13.000
And I know that if he pulled the trigger,

1982
02:10:13.000 --> 02:10:16.000
I would never have known it.

1983
02:10:16.000 --> 02:10:19.000
That would have been the end.

1984
02:10:19.000 --> 02:10:21.000
I'd been captured.

1985
02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:24.000
Now when I had no idea what to do, at least when I was on the run,

1986
02:10:24.000 --> 02:10:30.000
I knew where I was going, even fighting for my life was easier than giving up all control.

1987
02:10:30.000 --> 02:10:35.000
I was now at the mercy of the Chinese.

1988
02:10:35.000 --> 02:10:37.000
So there you go.

1989
02:10:37.000 --> 02:10:44.000
Captured.

1990
02:10:44.000 --> 02:10:47.000
There's nothing else you can do.

1991
02:10:47.000 --> 02:10:52.000
Nothing else you can do.

1992
02:10:52.000 --> 02:10:55.000
They muster some other guys that got captured.

1993
02:10:55.000 --> 02:10:57.000
They muster them all together.

1994
02:10:57.000 --> 02:10:58.000
Now we're going back to the book.

1995
02:10:58.000 --> 02:11:00.000
There are about 10 Chinese guards.

1996
02:11:00.000 --> 02:11:02.000
They lined up us.

1997
02:11:02.000 --> 02:11:06.000
They lined up beside us and moved us down the road a couple hundred yards.

1998
02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:11.000
Suddenly the one in the lead started yelling in the whole column stopped.

1999
02:11:11.000 --> 02:11:17.000
The guards grabbed us and made us kneel down in front of a ditch.

2000
02:11:17.000 --> 02:11:22.000
I could hear one of the soldiers barking what sounded like orders in Chinese.

2001
02:11:22.000 --> 02:11:25.000
My mind went on fuller.

2002
02:11:25.000 --> 02:11:29.000
They were going to execute us.

2003
02:11:29.000 --> 02:11:33.000
I felt the guy next to me shaking and another started sobbing.

2004
02:11:33.000 --> 02:11:36.000
My God, this is it.

2005
02:11:36.000 --> 02:11:41.000
This is one of those situations where you expect to see your life flash before your eyes.

2006
02:11:41.000 --> 02:11:45.000
I was ready to really, really have seen from my childhood.

2007
02:11:45.000 --> 02:11:47.000
Good times in Austria.

2008
02:11:47.000 --> 02:11:52.000
Anything to take my mind from Korea and this ditch.

2009
02:11:52.000 --> 02:11:55.000
They didn't happen to me.

2010
02:11:55.000 --> 02:11:59.000
I just closed my eyes.

2011
02:11:59.000 --> 02:12:04.000
Instead of shots, I heard laughing.

2012
02:12:04.000 --> 02:12:06.000
They motioned for us to get up.

2013
02:12:06.000 --> 02:12:10.000
The guy next to me was so emotionally drained that he couldn't get up.

2014
02:12:10.000 --> 02:12:13.000
I tried to help him, but my hands were tied behind my back.

2015
02:12:13.000 --> 02:12:15.000
Get up, I yelled.

2016
02:12:15.000 --> 02:12:18.000
Don't let them laugh at you.

2017
02:12:18.000 --> 02:12:21.000
Get up.

2018
02:12:21.000 --> 02:12:33.000
They get to like a little building and they've been carrying captured rifles this whole time.

